Title: Extracting Contigs from STS-Content Data by Revealing Hidden Interval Graph Structure  
Author: Eric Harley Anthony Bonner and Nathan Goodman Eric Harley 
Note: Contact:  
Abstract: Motivation: Contig mapping is an important and difficult problem in genomic technology. The data used to construct such maps contain numerous errors. No fully automated means to analyze such data yet exists. Results: This paper introduces a graph algorithm which creates a simplified view of physical mapping data. The shape of the resulting structure graph provides a quality check | coherent data produce a straight line, while anomalous data produce branches and loops. Besides being a useful rule of thumb, the method can help formalize steps taken in physical mapping. In cases where the data contain false positives creating a complex structure graph, it is sometimes possible to disentangle the various paths into subsets of the data covering contiguous regions of the genome, i.e., contigs. These straight subgraphs can then be analyzed in standard ways to construct a physical map. A theoretical basis for the method is presented along with examples of its application to current STS data from human genome centers. The technique has general applicability to any data that have an underlying (albeit noisy) interval model. Availability: Not applicable. 
